    {
      "line": 44,
      "text": "BY STEWART BRAND (WHOLE EARTH EDITOR, 1968-1984)"
    },
    {
      "line": 47,
      "text": "I HAVE A THEORY about theme issues"
    },
    {
      "line": 48,
      "text": "of magazines. I think they’re a bad idea."
    },
    {
      "line": 51,
      "text": "Once a theme issue announces its grand"
    },
    {
      "line": 52,
      "text": "exploration on the cover (“MEN - Will"
    },
    {
      "line": 53,
      "text": "They Ever Get Equal Rights?”), imme-"
    },
    {
      "line": 54,
      "text": "diately everyone uninterested in that"
    },
    {
      "line": 55,
      "text": "subject will be chased away, perhaps"
    },
    {
      "line": 56,
      "text": "forever. Those who are interested in the"
    },
    {
      "line": 57,
      "text": "subject are almost certain to be bored"
    },
    {
      "line": 58,
      "text": "by it by the end of the exhaustive treat-"
    },
    {
      "line": 61,
      "text": "ment. And some articles of so-so quality"
    },
    {
      "line": 64,
      "text": "are bound to be thrown in to fill out the"
    },
    {
      "line": 65,
      "text": "illusion of completeness, which then"
    },
    {
      "line": 66,
      "text": "degrades the whole enterprise. This is"
    },
    {
      "line": 67,
      "text": "why anthologies sell so badly as books;"
    },
    {
      "line": 68,
      "text": "readers are justifiably wary."
    },
    {
      "line": 71,
      "text": "So why do so many magazines do it?"
    },
    {
